The Jubilee Party has rescheduled its primaries from April 21, and it will now conduct them in two days due to logistics and administration challenges.The party will hold the nominations on April 21 and April 25.Speaking at the party headquarters yesterday, JP secretary general Raphael Tuju said the National Election Board has rescheduled a two-day process covering the original date, and a supplementary to reduce pressure on staff managing the exercise.&ldquo;We had planned to have our primaries on April 21 but it was somehow challenging and we agreed to have them in phases due to the resources required,&rdquo; Tuju said.On April 21, primaries will take place in Kirinyaga, Elgeyo Marakwet, Meru, Uasin Gishu, Baringo, Bomet, Laikipia, Murang&rsquo;a, Tharaka Nithi, Kiambu, Nyandarua, Embu, Kericho, West Pokot, Nandi, Nakuru, Nyeri, Nairobi, Kajiado, Narok, Trans-Nzoia and Taita Taveta. &ldquo;On April 21 we will do primaries in 22 counties, while on April 25 we will conduct primaries in 23 counties, &ldquo; JP National Election Board chairman Andrew Musangi said.On April 25, nominations will be held in Lamu, Wajir, Mandera, Marsabit, Turkana, Samburu, Kilifi, Tana River, Mombasa, Kitui, Machakos, Makueni, Kakamega, Vihiga, Bungoma, Busia, Homa Bay, Migori, Kwale, Garissa, Nyamira, Isiolo and Kisii.&ldquo;Aspirants are reminded that acts of violence before, during or after the primaries will lead to automatic disqualification,&rdquo; Musangi said.The hotly contested regions will hold the exercise on April 25. The deadline for parties to submit to the Independent Electoral Boundaries Commission names of aspirants who will run in the August polls is April 25. JP will not conduct primaries in Kisumu and Siaya because most of the positions have one aspirant or did not have more than two aspirants.&ldquo;We will not use smart cards during the primaries,&rdquo; Musangi said. Returning officers have been shuffled and will not be permitted to serve in their own constituencies as from today.